AGI - Israeli forces arrested &nbsp;Hamdan Ballal>, one of the co-registers of the Oscar-winning documentary film "No Other Land>", while he was in treatment in an ambulance in Massafer Yatta> (Used West Bank), because he was attacked and beaten by a group of settlers. The film producer reported it.
<h2>Denunciation of Yuval Abraham</h2>
"A group of settlers just fired Hamdan Ballal. They beat him. He has head and stomach wounds. The soldiers assaulted the ambulance he called and took him away. Since then there is no trace of him," Yuval> Abraham, the Israeli co-director of the film, denounced on his X account.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2> Attack on the village of Susiya</h2>
According to the film's production company, events occurred around 18 on Monday 24 March when a dozen Israeli settlers attacked the Palestinian village, Susiya>, Masafer Yatta>, wounding people and destroying property.
"The group of attackers arrived with manganelli, knives and at least one assault rifle; many were also masked. Five Jewish American activists went to the place to document the attack and were violently attacked by settlers, who also used stones to destroy their vehicle with activists inside," reads in the note.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2> Ballal</h2>
During the attack, Ballal was wounded "by blood and swelling" and while the paramedics treated him, the Israeli forces arrested him along with another Palestinian. The production house doesn't know where Ballal is and if he's getting medical attention.
<h2 The documentary "No Other Land"</h2>
"No Other Land" covers five years of recordings (2019-2023) at the home of Palestinian journalist Basel Adra> in the group of villages of Masafer Yatta, in the occupied West Bank, showing the demolitions of houses, schools, water wells and roads by the Israeli army and which continue today.
On March 3, the film won the Oscar for the best documentary and since then the group of Israeli-Palestinian activists Standing Together> has organized screenings in Tel Aviv and other cities of the country, after Israeli Culture Minister Miki Zohar> asked Israeli cinemas not to project the film.
